Great prompt. Because you‚Äôre only trading the concession into the auction and it‚Äôs per bond, you need a box that isolates that bond‚Äôs relative value (RV) versus an appropriate benchmark ‚Äî not a generic 10s2s every time.

Here‚Äôs the intuitive rule and a precise way to implement it.

Intuition (what box should you trade?)

For a given auction bond, you want to strip out broad curve moves (level/slope) and measure its sector-relative cheap/rich into T. The cleanest way is:

Per-bond ASW box = Bond‚Äôs ASW ‚àí (weighted combination of nearby swap pillars‚Äô ASW)

The nearby pillars are the two standard swap maturities that bracket the bond‚Äôs maturity at the auction date (e.g., a 9.7y bond is bracketed by 7y and 10y pillars).

The weights are chosen so the benchmark tracks the bond‚Äôs curve beta (neutralizing level/slope). Two good choices:

Linear maturity weights (fast & robust)

DV01-matched weights (best practice if you have DV01s)

That residual is the bond-specific box you should trade.

If you already computed a curve-fitted ASW residual (your curve_resid), that is the per-bond ASW box. You can use it directly.

Practical selection rules (what do I do today?)
Tier 1 ‚Äî Exact (recommended)

Find bracketing swap pillars for each bond at its auction date:

