Short answer: yes‚Äîuse calendar time for the backtest plots, not event‚Äêtime.
Event-time (rel_day = ‚àí10‚Ä¶+10) is perfect for the analysis (concession profiles), but a backtest should show performance when it actually happens in real time. Because you only trade around auctions (not every day), your equity curve will be step-like with gaps‚Äîthis is expected.

Below are two sensible x-axes you can use, plus drop-in code for each.

Option A ‚Äî Cumulative P&L by exit (auction) date (simple, standard)

One row = one trade (enter on P2/P1, exit on T).

Allocate each trade‚Äôs P&L to its exit date (when it‚Äôs realized).

X-axis = exit_date (i.e., auction_dt).

Result: step-function equity curve over the last year; no fake interpolation on days you weren‚Äôt trading.

# assumes you already have:
# trades: from backtest_carry_in_last_year(...), with columns ['auction_dt','series_id','pnl_bp', ...]
# panel:  event panel with ['auction_dt','series_id','date','rel_day'] so we can fetch entry dates

def attach_trade_dates(trades, panel, pre_col="P2"):
    entry_rel = -2 if pre_col == "P2" else -1
    dates = panel[panel["rel_day"].isin([entry_rel, 0])][["auction_dt","series_id","rel_day","date"]]
    pivot = (dates.pivot_table(index=["auction_dt","series_id"],
                               columns="rel_day", values="date", aggfunc="first")
                  .rename(columns={entry_rel:"entry_date", 0:"exit_date"})
                  .reset_index())
    return trades.merge(pivot, on=["auction_dt","series_id"], how="left")

# build dated trades and an equity curve (calendar time)
dated_trades = attach_trade_dates(trades, panel, pre_col="P2")
eq = (dated_trades.sort_values("exit_date")
                  .assign(cum_pnl_bp=lambda d: d["pnl_bp"].cumsum())
                  [["exit_date","cum_pnl_bp"]])

# (plot) x-axis = exit_date; y-axis = cumulative P&L (bp)
# plt.figure(...); plt.step(eq["exit_date"], eq["cum_pnl_bp"], where="post"); ...


When to show: headline equity curve, bucket-segmented curves (filter dated_trades by bucket then repeat).

Option B ‚Äî Daily mark-to-market equity curve (optional, more granular)

If you want to display drawdowns during the holding period (P2‚ÜíT or P1‚ÜíT), you can build a daily P&L series by allocating each trade‚Äôs P&L on its exit day only (simple) or, more precisely, by MTM the box within the holding window and summing across trades.

Given carry-in trades last 1‚Äì2 days, the exit-day allocation is usually enough. If you insist on MTM:

def daily_equity_exit_allocation(dated_trades):
    # allocate the whole trade P&L to its exit date (clean step series)
    daily = (dated_trades.groupby("exit_date")["pnl_bp"].sum()
                        .sort_index()
                        .rename("pnl_bp")
                        .to_frame())
    daily["cum_pnl_bp"] = daily["pnl_bp"].cumsum()
    return daily.reset_index()

daily_curve = daily_equity_exit_allocation(dated_trades)
# Plot: x = date, y = cum_pnl_bp (will be flat between exits)


If you really want in-window MTM, you can reconstruct daily box changes from panel["box_perbond"] between entry_date and exit_date, multiply by dir, and subtract costs on entry. For carry-in (1‚Äì2 days), this rarely changes the story.

How to explain this in your presentation

‚ÄúFor event-study plots we use trading-day event time (rel_day) to show average concession.
For the backtest, we switch to calendar time because trades only occur around auctions. We therefore plot cumulative P&L by exit (auction) date; the equity curve is step-like (no positions on most days).‚Äù

‚ÄúEach trade‚Äôs P&L is computed from entry at P2/P1 to exit at T, in bp of the per-bond ASW box, minus a round-trip cost. We then sort trades by exit date and cumulate to get the equity curve. Optionally, we can build a daily MTM series, but for 1‚Äì2-day holds, exit-day allocation is sufficient and cleaner.‚Äù

Quick checklist

‚úÖ Event-study charts: keep x-axis = rel_day.

‚úÖ Backtest equity curve: x-axis = calendar date (prefer exit/auction date).

‚úÖ Don‚Äôt fabricate daily points when you‚Äôre not in a trade; a step line is expected.

‚úÖ If stakeholders want intra-window swings, add the optional daily MTM.

If you want, share your current equity plot and I‚Äôll tweak it to use exit dates and a step style so it reads cleanly.

